text: The first 'Sinister' was terrifying because unlike most of the movies around showed the triumph of evil, which is by itself disturbing; however, contrary to the prequel, Baghool is no more the hazy evil who perpetrated our world thru his images, or representations, which I feel denigrates its antagonism, as it makes of Baghool something existing, bringing in to par with other monsters we have seen in other 'horror' movies. People are more afraid of what they cannot understand, of what they cannot manipulate, destroy or counter - this is what made Baghool more terrifying, but, if you bring it out of the metaphysical realms, it's just another monster, we are made to figure out. The trailer alone makes me feel like not wanting to watch the movie, and if I'm correct, it's not going to be as good as its predecessor.¬†

text: I liked the first film, it gave a few decent scares, had a fantastic soundtrack and managed to build a palpable sense of dread in the viewer. Up until the last 20 minutes or so that is, where it ultimately fell a bit flat in an effort to explain the plot. The problem I see with this trailer, is that Bagul, the creepy mysterious demon from the first film, is revealed far to often. It's really the cardinal sin of horror films, you don't expose the viewers to a supernatural antagonist too often, as it lessens the impact of their appearance each time. I have some hope, the film at least has the premise of an investigation which always helps to carry the plot in horror films, but I feel that Bagul may be reduced from the startling and terrifying figure unexpectedly revealed in a swimming pool, to (queue the trailers music) just another generic boogeyman.

text: Its very rare to see a horror movie sequal that surpasses the original. Mainly because you can only do one of two things: have the villain lose, in which case you more or less 'kill' any hopes for a reasonable franchise... OR, you essentially turn the villain into the hero, like was done with Jason or Freddie.  The problem then becomes that you're really just watching a movie about people being murdered with no other opportunities to see an actual plot. I'm hoping they didn't just turn this into a 'lets find new ways to murder people' sort of movie for the sake of more sequels...but it sure looked that way.  I guess the moral of the box office is "why make one or two good movies when you can make 7 terrible ones?"

text: MASSIVE SPOILERS : I remember from reading the script, the highlight of the movie is the tape that takes place in a church. Long story short, a family has rats on their stomach, a bowl is placed on top of the rats, the top of the bowl is heated with a piece of coal and the rats burrow through their stomachs. It was absolutely sickening to read so expect that to be the scariest part of the movie.  Other than that, Fishing Trip involves alligators and it's pretty corny, the dentist one (the drill seen here) is pretty gross and the kitchen electrocution is sort of fucked up but about the same level as the tapes from the first. The film opened with a hanging family set on fire and there's one pretty tame tape about a family being buried in the snow and left to die of hypothermia.¬†  All in all, the tapes are better but the Baghul stuff is ridiculous and stupid and overdone, the ghost kids are too prominent and the characters are sort of poorly developed. It's definitely earning it's R rating so no fears there, I just thought I would let people who want to know spoilers what they're in for with the film this time around since I knew all about it from the script.

text: Definitely not feeling this one as much as the first... The first one was disturbing until it turned into "demons and ghosts and paranormal."  This one seems to completely focus on paranormal bullcrap and jump-scares.  I liked to believe there was a murder to be solved in the first movie, and demon worshippers were to blame. Bughuul is a creepy idea but ideas are scary when you're not face-to-face and focused on them the entire movie. It seems more like a thriller/sci-fi now, IMO.  Don't even get me started on insidious, that movie was freaky as hell until the demon was some guy in red paint in front of the camera. Why does there have to be a climax, a resolution, a face-to-face conflict with demons? It's scarier to me just thinking about the idea of demons and creepy things, not seeing crappy Hollywood actors dressed up.  /horror movie rant

text: The problem isn't with the period of horror genre we are in now but the people watching it. Horror films have been done for such a long time now that cliches have become a staple, why? because most set-ups and plots have been done already. Horror film producers have nothing else to go on than make it as thrilling and engaging as possible. Sometimes, we just have to lower our own standards (just not too much though) because deep down you chose that film to be entertained but you let your own high standards get the best of you. Goddamnit! just enjoy the film as it is.  FYI, I did enjoy watching this. I'm a pretty decent horror film fan and I think this was WORTH a watch.

text: Reason why this film sucks. Spoiler:  The 'actors' suck.
